Me and my brother, Cornelis de Witt, got lynched by an angry mob in The Hague in 1672. Our body parts like heart and fingers were removed to be exposed as souvenirs, while other parts were roasted and eaten by the hysterical crowd. Our corpses were eventually hung upside down on a scaffold nearby.

I was a political leader, director of foreign and fiscal policies for the United Provinces, and leader of a party committed to „True Freedom.“ In the years of peace I tried to strengthen Dutch finances and encourage trade and shipping.

I had been the most powerful man in the Republic for close to twenty years, steadfastly supported by my brother Cornelis. But we were held responsible for everything that went wrong in the year 1672. Also known as the „Year of Disaster“.
